### Recommendation: Use `TimeProvider` (built-in)

Since you're on **net10.0**, the built-in `TimeProvider` abstract class is the ideal solution — zero extra NuGet packages needed.

**How it works:**

```csharp
public class OrderProcessor
{
    private readonly TimeProvider _timeProvider;
    private readonly ILogger<OrderProcessor> _logger;

    public OrderProcessor(ILogger<OrderProcessor> logger, TimeProvider timeProvider)
    {
        _logger = logger;
        _timeProvider = timeProvider;
    }

    public Order CreateOrder(string customerId, decimal amount)
    {
        var now = _timeProvider.GetUtcNow();
        var order = new Order
        {
            Id = Guid.NewGuid().ToString(),
            CustomerId = customerId,
            Amount = amount,
            CreatedAt = now.UtcDateTime,
            ExpiresAt = now.AddDays(30).UtcDateTime
        };
        // ...
    }

    public bool IsExpired(Order order)
    {
        return _timeProvider.GetUtcNow() > order.ExpiresAt;
    }
}
```

**In tests**, use `Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing.FakeTimeProvider`:

```csharp
var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var processor = new OrderProcessor(logger, fakeTime);

var order = processor.CreateOrder("cust-1", 99.99m);
Assert.Equal(new DateTime(2026, 1, 15), order.CreatedAt.Date);

// Advance time to test expiration
fakeTime.Advance(TimeSpan.FromDays(31));
Assert.True(processor.IsExpired(order));
```

**In production DI**: `services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);`

